Comparing Plant Growth Between Treatments

In this experiment plants were grown in three groups. Two groups were given plant treatments to test for its effect on the growth of the plant, then the third set acted as a control. The plants were then dried, and weighed to determine which treatment had higher growth enhancement to organic matter.

Density Plot of Dried Plant Weight

The following Plot compares the control, and the two treatments dried plant weights by density and illustrates the variance and effectiveness of each group.

g <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(weight))
levels(g[["data"]][["group"]])[levels(g[["data"]][["group"]])=="ctrl"]<-"Control"
levels(g[["data"]][["group"]])[levels(g[["data"]][["group"]])=="trt1"]<-"Treatment 1"
levels(g[["data"]][["group"]])[levels(g[["data"]][["group"]])=="trt2"]<-"Treatment 2"
g + geom_density(aes(fill=factor(group)), alpha=0.8) + 
     labs(title="Density plot", 
          subtitle="Plant Growth with Treatments",
          caption="Source: PlantGrowth",
          x="Dried Plant Weight",
          fill="Treatment Group")+facet_wrap(~ group)

PlantGrowth Summary

summary(PlantGrowth)
##      weight       group   
##  Min.   :3.590   ctrl:10  
##  1st Qu.:4.550   trt1:10  
##  Median :5.155   trt2:10  
##  Mean   :5.073            
##  3rd Qu.:5.530            
##  Max.   :6.310

PlantGrowth Synopsis

Overall, of the 30 total records in the PlantGrowth data set. The Control group has 10 samples, the Treatment 1 group has 10, and the Treatment 2 has 10 samples. Each group has the following means: by 5.032, 4.661, 5.526 . This clearly shows that Treatment 2 is superiour to Treatment 1, and that Treatment 1 even diminishes plant growth compared to the control. It would seems Treatment 2 is close to Miracle Grow, while Treatment 1 is more akin to RoundUp!

This dataset measures the height of Loblolly Pines over 25 years. My yard is full of Loblolly Pines, and I thought it would be interesting to guessimate the age of my trees based off this dataset. My trees are at least 60 feet tall, perhaps even 80!

Line Chart of Loblolly Pines over 25 Years

The following line chart plots the growth of the 14 seeds over the 25 year span.

l + geom_line( alpha=0.8) +

Circumference Growth of Orange Trees

Now that we have measured plant weight and height, let us measure and explore girth or circumference. Oranges, being my favorite fruit (up there with bananas but there are no banana data sets). The Orange data set measures orange trees circumference over days since 12/31/1968 for a total of 1582 days.

Violin Chart of Orange Tree Circumference

The following violin chart plots the growth of the 5 trees circumference over a span of 1582 days. I chose the violin chart to illustrate the increase of width (girth) as time increases and faceted on each Tree.

ggplot(Orange, aes(circumference, age)) + 
   geom_violin(aes(fill = Tree)) + facet_grid(~Tree) + 
     labs(title="Orange Tree Circumference", 
          subtitle="Thickness Over Days",
          caption="Source: Orange", 
          y="Tree Age (days)",
          x="Tree Circumference (mm)")

Orange Summary

Orange Synopsis

Overall, of the 35 total records in the Orange data Each of the 5 trees was measured on average of every 244 days.

The trees grew on average of 24mm per measurement period, with the largest gain of 55mm (by tree 4) and the smallest of 0mm (tree 2).At the end of the time span the average circumference of the Orange Tree is 175.8 mm. Which is only 6.9inches, so orange trees are pretty thin on average.

The Effect of Vitamin C on Tooth Growth in Guinea Pigs

This time we are moving onto a different animal, and literally an animal. Since we just talked about oranges (which are very high in vitamin C) lets measure the effect of vitamin C on the tooth growth of the guinea pig. The ToothGrowth data set is a response is the length of odontoblasts (cells responsible for tooth growth) in 60 guinea pigs. Each animal received one of three dose levels of vitamin C (0.5, 1, and 2 mg/day) by one of two delivery methods, orange juice or ascorbic acid

Bar Chart of Tooth Growth in Guinea Pigs

The following violin chart plots the growth of the 5 trees circumference over the time span. I chose the violin chart to illustrate the increase of width (girth) as time increases and faceted on each Tree.

t <- ggplot(ToothGrowth, aes(dose, len))
t + geom_boxplot(aes(fill=factor(dose))) +geom_jitter(width = .02)+ geom_smooth(aes(dose,len),fullrange = TRUE,position = "dodge") + facet_grid(~supp)+
   labs(title="Smooth Box plot", 
        subtitle="ToothGrowth: Length vs. Dose per Supplement",
        caption="Source: ToothGrowth",
        x="Dose(mg/day)",
        y="Length(um)")

Tooth Summary

Tooth Synopsis

Overall, of the 55 total records in the Tooth data. There are 3 columns, supp is a factor with VC, OJ as values. Dose has distinct values of 0.5, 1, 2. The following table has min/max of tooth growth per dose

Dose Min Max
0.5 4.2 21.5
1.0 13.6 27.3
2.0 18.5 33.9

The average tooth growth length by supplement category is 20.6633333, 16.9633333 (OJ, VC respectively). The orange juice supplement promotes more growth in general compared to the absorbic acid (VC).
